The U.S. economy added 228,000 jobs in November, with gains seen across all sectors except information and utilities. The unemployment rate remained steady at 4.1 percent, the lowest it has been in over 16 years. Hispanic workers experienced a record low unemployment rate of 4.7 percent, the lowest in at least 44 years. Manufacturing jobs saw a significant increase, with 31,000 jobs added in November and 171,000 jobs added in 2017. The construction industry also saw growth, adding 24,000 jobs in November and 138,000 jobs since January. Average weekly hours remained relatively unchanged, while average hourly earnings for private sector workers increased by 5 cents, a 2.5 percent increase compared to the previous year. The labor force participation rate remained unchanged, while the LFPR for prime-aged individuals increased by 0.2 percentage points. The report suggests that the growth in real GDP is leading to more employment opportunities for American workers.